'''Frances Borzello''' is a British [[History of art|art historian]] and scholar, feminist [[art critic]] and author. Her work specializes in the social history of art, and includes study on the social position of European woman artists in the context of their society, the study of female self-portraits and female nudes.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/books/reclaiming-the-self-through-art/158993.article|title=Reclaiming the self through art|last=Purvis|first=June|date=1999-02-05|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en}}</ref> She authored the book ''Seeing Ourselves: Women's Self Portraits,'' which has been continuously published since 1998 and has 30 editions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n86042939/|title=Borzello, Frances|last=|first=|date=|website=OCLC World Cat|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref> Her work widely recognized as contribution to the fields of [[art history]] and [[women's studies]]. 

== Biography ==
Borzello earned her [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the [[University College London]] in 1980.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mD8rDwAAQBAJ&dq|title=Printing and Painting the News in Victorian London: "The Graphic and Social Realism, 1869-1891|last=Korda|first=Andrea|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=1351553240|location=|pages=14|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> Her [[Thesis|dissertation]] published in 1981 and was titled, "The relationship of fine art and the poor in late nineteenth century England".<ref>{{Cite thesis|last=Borzello|first=Frances|title=The relationship of fine art and the poor in late nineteenth century England|date=1981|publisher=Document Supply Centre, British Library|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/relationship-of-fine-art-and-the-poor-in-late-nineteenth-century-england/oclc/501940803&referer=brief_results|place=Boston Spa, England|language=English}}</ref> Borzello was a member of a women's photography group founded in the 1970s called ''Second Sight,'' which included members such as [[Annette Kuhn]], [[Jill Pack]], and [[Cassandra Wedd]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Power of the Image: Essays on Representation and Sexuality|last=Kuhn|first=Annette|publisher=Routledge|year=2017|isbn=1136137645|location=|pages=9-10}}</ref>

Borzello's writing "Preaching to the converted? Feminist art publishing in the 1980s," was included in the 1995 book ''[[New Feminist Art Criticism: Critical Strategies]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/New_Feminist_Art_Criticism.html?id=qZOfAAAAMAAJ|title=New feminist art criticism: critical strategies|last=Deepwell|first=Kate|date=1995|publisher=Manchester University Press|year=|isbn=9780719042577|location=|pages=|language=en|via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref>

Her book first published in 1998,<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/apr/11/rachel-cooke-shelf-life-borzello-seeing-ourselves-women-self-portraits-valadon-sherman-wilke|title=Seeing Ourselves: from Boccaccio to the age of the selfie|last=Cooke|first=Rachel|date=2016-04-11|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref> ''Seeing Ourselves: Women's Self Portraits'' discusses women creating their own images and the power of self-portrait rather than being portrayed as objects, as well as a historical look at gender, identity and representation.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/who-does-she-think-she-is-1154437.html|title=Who does she think she is?|last=Moore|first=Suzanne|date=April 4, 1998|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-06-11|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/self-regard-1.144432|title=Self-regard|last=O'Sullivan|first=Niamh|date=January 9, 1999|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-06-12|language=en-US}}</ref> The book is an in-depth look at history, starting with the self-portraits of [[Middle Ages|Medieval]] nuns and eventually ending in the 21st century, the book is acknowledging themes in the self portraits including motherhood, female beauty, musical talents as seen in early work and in the 20th century themes of sexuality, pain, race, gender and disease.<ref name=":1" /> Some artists in the book ''Seeing Ourselves: Women's Self Portraits'' include: [[Judith Leyster]], [[Anna Dorothea Therbusch]], [[Marie-Nicole Vestier|Marie-Nicole Dumont]], [[Hortense Haudebourt-Lescot]], [[Suzanne Valadon]], [[Gwen John]], [[Paula Modersohn-Becker]], [[Charlotte Berend-Corinth]], [[Frida Kahlo]], [[Wanda Wulz]], [[Charlotte Salomon]], [[Judy Chicago]], [[Jo Spence]], [[Hannah Wilke]], [[Carolee Schneemann]], [[Cindy Sherman]], [[Tracey Emin]] and more.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nacion.com/ancora/la-fridamania-toma-la-web/OU7H6YT3MBATNCGJFC2ETWCJEY/story/|title=La Fridamanía toma la web: Así es la más grande retrospectiva digital sobre Frida Kahlo|work=La Nación, Grupo Nación|access-date=2018-06-13|language=es-LA}}</ref><ref name=":2" /> The 2016 edition of ''Seeing Ourselves: Women's Self Portraits'' is fully revised and includes a new [[afterword]] by the author about [[Selfie|selfies]].<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.spectator.co.uk/2016/03/sexy-selfies-through-the-ages/|title=Sexy selfies through the ages|last=|first=|date=2016-03-26|work=The Spectator|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>

The 2010 book, ''Frida Kahlo: Face to Face'' was co-authored with American artist [[Judy Chicago]], and focused on Frida Kahlo's career as well as Kahlo's artwork in relation to topics like female self portraiture and commercialization.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artnews.com/2014/07/14/saving-frida-kahlo-from-her-own-celebrity/|title=Saving Frida Kahlo From Her Own Celebrity|last=Miranda|first=Carolina A.|date=2014-07-14|website=ARTnews|language=en-US|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://blog.nmwa.org/2010/10/20/face-to-face-with-frida-kahlo-judy-chicago-and-frances-borzello/|title=Face to Face with Frida Kahlo, Judy Chicago, and Frances Borzello|last=|first=|date=2010-10-20|work=Broad Strokes: [[The National Museum of Women in the Arts]]|access-date=2018-06-13|language=en-US}}</ref>

