{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} '''Leo Marx''' (born November 15, 1919) is an American professor who worked at the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] and was an author known for his works in the field of [[American studies]]. His work in American studies examines the relationship between technology and culture in 19th- and 20th-century America. He graduated from Harvard University with a B.A. in History and Literature and a PhD in the History of American Civilization in 1950.
== Selected bibliography == * Marx, Leo (1964). ''[[The Machine in the Garden: Technology and the Pastoral Ideal in America]]''. New York: Oxford University Press. * Marx, Leo (1989). ''The Pilot and the Passenger: Essays on Literature, Technology, and Culture in the United States''. New York: Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|9780195048766}}. * Marx, Leo; [[Merritt Roe Smith|Smith, Merritt R.]] (1994). ''Does Technology Drive History? The Dilemma of Technological Determinism''. Cambridge, Massachusetts: MIT Press. {{ISBN|9780262691673}}. * {{cite book | last1 = Marx | first1 = Leo | last2 = Mazlish | first2 = Bruce | title = Progress: Fact or Illusion | publisher = University of Michigan Press | location = Ann Arbor | year = 1998 | isbn = 9780472085095 }} * {{cite book | last1 = Marx | first1 = Leo | last2 = Conway | first2 = Jill | last3 = Keniston | first3 = Kenneth | author-link2 = Jill Ker Conway | title = Earth, Air, Fire, Water: Humanistic Studies of the Environment | publisher = University of Massachusetts Press | location = Amherst | year = 1999 | isbn = 9781558492219 }}
